DIV2.P:
THE Gospel exceeds the Law, not only in an acci∣dental or adventitious, but also an intrinsick Glory. The Law was not only made glorious in the Eyes of the Children of Israel, by the dignity of the Person and lustre on the face of Moses, by whom it came, and the manner of its delivery, but it was glorious in it self; being a Revelation from GOD of his Ex∣cellencies to his Creatures, and his Will concerning them: But the Gospel is more glorious in it self, being a clearer, and more compleat Revelation of GOD'S Glory. This is hinted by the Apostle in our Context, where he is shewing how the Gospel exceeds the Law in Glory, v. 18. But we all with open face, beholding as in a Glass the Glory of the Lord. Moses put a Vail over his Face, when he came down from the Mount, that so all the Glory of his Countenance might not be seen, might not this represent GOD'S concealing from the Jewish People much of his Glory, which was afterwards to be manifested? v. 13. Moses put a Vail over his face, that the Children of Israel could not stedfastly look to the end of that which is abolished. They had but an obscure View of the Mystery of CHRIST, which was vailed under the Types and Shadows of the Ceremonial Law; like as the Glory on the face of Moses was vailed. v. 14 But their Minds were blinded: for until this day re∣maineth the same vail untaken away, in the reading of the Old Testament: which vail is done away in Christ. The vail of outward Shadows and Types was removed, by Christ's coming into the World: for then the Prefigurations, Prophesies and Promises of the Messiah were fulfilled, and the Glory of GOD in our Redemption by Christ was to be clearly seen: But the vail of spiritual Blindness on the Minds and Hearts of the Jews, which was also mystically


signified by the Vail upon the face of Moses, remains to this day in their reading the Old Testament, which hinders them from discovering the Messiah to be already come, and that the Types and Prophesies are accomplished in him. But we all with open face, all we who believe have the Vail removed from us, so that with open face we behold the Glory of the Lord as in a Glass, i. e. in the Gospel, which is as a Glass, not a Perspective thro' which things afar off are darkly seen, but a Looking-glass fully representing the face as near. The Glory of the Lord, which was vail'd and cover'd under the Types and Shadows of the Law, is now by the Gospel clearly revealed. And how Chris∣tians do in the Gospel, as it is a Glass, see the Glory of GOD, the Apostle telleth us, 2 Cor. 4.6. For GOD who Commanded the light to shine out of dark∣ness, hath shined in our , to give the light of the knowledge of the glory of GOD, in face of Jesus Christ. By the face of Jesus Christ, in which the Glory of GOD is seen, the Apostle seems to allude to that divine Lustre with which the Face of Moses shone, when he came down from Mount Sinai: So that his meaning may be this, That as the Children of Israel with their bodily Eyes saw something of GOD'S Glory shining in the Face of Moses; so they the Disciples of our Saviour, did more clearly with the Eyes of their enlightned Understandings behold the divine Glory in Jesus Christ, whose Face the Glass of the Gospel represented to them. Christ is the brightness of God's Glory, and the express Image of his Person. There is no Perfection in GOD, which is not in Christ, for Christ is GOD. And in that Glass wherein we see the Face of Christ who is thus the Image of GOD, we behold the Glory of GOD; and in the Gospel of Jesus Christ is more clearly revealed. By the Law Men might discern, as it were GOD'S Back-parts. As He said unto Moses, who beseeched the LORD to shew him his Glory, Exod. 33.23. Thou shalt see my back-parts: but my Face shall not be seen: But in the Gospel we may see the Face of Jesus Christ, and so the Face of GOD;


for CHRIST is the adequate and essential Image of GOD. The knowledge of Christ, and so of GOD'S Glory, which could be obtain'd by the Writings of Moses and the Prophets, was small, compar'd with that which the Gospel affords; and did not the New Testament expound the Old, wou'd not the Vail on the face of Moses, as to us, remain untaken away.

DIV1.P:
IT is true, that many who remain in their natural Condition, do appear righteous in the eye of the World;


but they are not so in the sight of GOD: They may be outwardly clean; may wash the out-side of the Cup and Platter, and garnish the Sepulchre with spe∣cious shews of Devotion; but are inwardly defiled, full of all Uncleanness, spiritual Putrefaction, Hypo∣crisy and Iniquity, Luke 16.15. He said unto them, Ye are they which justifie your selves before men; but God knoweth your hearts: for that which is highly esteemed amongst men, is abomintion in the sight of God. Further, As all unconverted Sinners are, in respect of the Pollution of their Nature, in spiritual Sodom, so many of them may be fitly said to be so, in regard of the actual Defilements which they wal∣low in. The Soil of corrupt Nature yieldeth the Fruits of Sodom, Deut. 32.32. Their vine is of the vine of Sodom, and of the fields of Gomorrah: their grapes are grapes of gall, their clusters are bitter. Such are addressed as Inhabitants of Sodom & Gomor∣rah, who practis'd the Sins which abounded there, Isa. 1.10. Hear the word of the Lord, ye rulers of Sodom; give ear unto the law of our God, ye peo∣ple of Gomorrah. The Rulers and People of Israel had made themselves in respect of Sin, like those of Sodom and Gomorrah, therefore the faithful Prophet gave them this Title: They deserved no better. Rome is called Sodom for it's resembling it in Whordom, and all filthiness both of Flesh and Spirit, Rev. 11.8. Their dead bodies shall lie in the street of the great , which spiritually is called Sodom. What Multitudes are there who live in the Practice of the abominable Sins of Sodom, Pride, fulness of Bread, (i. e. Excess in Meats and Drinks,) abundance of Idleness, Uncharitableness and Oppression? How many, like the People of Sodom, give themselves over unto Laciviousness, to work all Uncleanness with greediness? How many declare their Sin as Sodom, and hide it not? Their Foreheads are steel'd with Impudence, they boast of their Wickedness, and glory in their Shame. How wretchedly secure are the most in the State of Nature, as the People were in Sodom? They are setled on their filthy Lees, quiet & undisturb'd


in their Sins, giving themselves up wholly to secular Business, and sensual Delights. As it was in the days of Lot; they did eat, they drank, they bought, they sold, they planted, they builded, not fearing Destructi∣on till it was brought upon them: Even so it is also in the days of the Son of Man.
